post_text:
Eric Zylman, STEM teacher at College Station Middle School, was awarded Teacher of the Year by the Air Force Association’s Aggieland Chapter. He received a certificate, cash award and a pin along with a chance to win another award at the national level.

The purpose of the program is to recognize classroom teachers at the chapter and state level for their accomplishments and achievements in exciting K-12 students about science, technology, engineering, and math (STEM), and preparing students to use and contribute to tomorrow's technologies. This is a unique opportunity for chapters to recognize and reward outstanding teachers who are furthering excellence in making coming to class an adventure. #SuccessCSISD

shared_text:
Brazos Valley Food Bank
May 20 at 9:51 AM ·

The COVID-19 pandemic has changed a lot of things. But one thing that it has not changed is the generosity of others. College Station I.S.D. - its administrators, teachers, counselor, students, parents and of course PTO members made another HUGE impact on the Brazos Valley Food Bank this year.

Every year, CSISD conducts a very competitive City-Wide PTO Food & Fund Drive. All of the College Station schools participate, collecting canned goods and raising money. Because of the pandemic, and students sheltering in place, this event was impossible to do in the same way as the past. We were not even sure if it would happen at all.

But, Dawn Ament and so many others charged forward. And, look what you accomplished together? OMG😲

This is over 115,000 meals!!!!

Thank you, from the bottom of our 💞! Have a safe and happy summer! #bvfoodbank

Kindness counts. Now more than ever.

REMINDER: CSISD will serve lunch at no cost to students ages 1-18 March 16-20. Students from any CSISD campus can pick up a meal at the front door of the following campuses between 11 a.m. and 1 p.m.: South Knoll, College Hills, Southwood Valley, River Bend and Oakwood.

Beginning, Tuesday, March 17, students who pick up a lunch will also receive a breakfast in a bag for the following day.

Beginning later this week, the Brazos Valley Food Bank will be at the five campus locations during the same two-hour window to provide non-perishable food items for families to take home.

P.S.-- Thanks to whoever created this graphic and originally posted it to social media!

The feedback provided by parents and community members will be shared with the instructional materials review team before resources are selected.

post_text:
The College Station FFA Meat Judging Team dominated over the competition in the meat judging contest at the Fort Worth Stock Show and Rodeo, winning by an outstanding 51 points with a team score of 1,974 out of 2,040 possible points. The top team consisted of seniors Meagan McMurray (1st high individual) and Cassity Brown (11th high individual), junior Kaitlyn Kotrla and sophomore Nathan Kerth (3rd high individual).

A second team of sophomores Hayden Bennett, Karli Kaase, and Caden Brown earned 11th place out of the 46 teams made up of 152 individuals from around the state.

Competitors evaluated classes of beef, pork, and lamb carcasses, beef ribs, pork loins and beef ribeye steaks, while also answering 10 questions over the pork and lamb carcass classes. They quality and yield graded six beef carcasses and identified 30 retail cuts of beef, pork, and lamb.

#SuccessCSISD

post_text: CSHS student Camille Chiu recently competed at the International Science and Engineering Fair in Phoenix, Arizona. Only 1,800 high school students from around the world are selected to compete at ISEF. This year, 80 countries and territories were represented. Camille earned an honorable mention in her respective category, Physics and Astronomy, with her project "Testing the Accuracy of the Tangent Point Method for Determining the Milky Way's Rotation Curve." Camille is coached by her AP Chemistry teacher, Casey Akin.

post_text:
Eight CSISD Project Search students participated in the annual Bridging Ceremony today, marking the end of their internship. Project Search is a partnership with Baylor/Scott & White, CSISD and other community organizations to help students with disabilities who are 18 years old and older develop independent living and workplace skills.

Project Search allows students the opportunity to have varied workplace experiences including environmental control, food service, and work in and around operating rooms. Through these experiences, students find and develop skills that can be transferred into future employment as well as find the types of employment that best suit them.

#SuccessCSISD

Tickets are $5 and concessions will be sold at intermission.

Interested in registering your PK-5th grade student for CSISD’s Summer Enrichment program this summer?

Please visit our Summer Enrichment website for more information on the program, session dates, FAQs, and registration/payment.

https://www.csisd.org/schools/other/summer_schools_camps/summer_enrichment/summer_enrichment_registration

Please Note: you will need to set up an account in Home Access Center in order to register and submit payment for Summer Enrichment. Your HAC account must be created 24 hours prior to submitting payment for any summer program. If you do not already have a HAC account created, please see the steps outlined on the website under the Summer Enrichment Registration tab.

(HAC accounts are currently used by many CSISD parents to monitor their student’s grades and attendance)

Questions? Email enrichmentss@csisd.org

post_text:
As part of Proclamation 2019, CSISD is reviewing instructional materials for the following subject areas:
English, Language Arts, and Reading (K-8)
Spanish, Language Arts, and Reading (K-6)
Handwriting (English and Spanish, grades K-5)

The adopted materials will be used in classrooms beginning with the 2019–20 school year.

Parents and community members are invited to view and provide feedback on the materials under consideration on February 20 from 3:00-7:00 in the Central Training Room at Central Office.

The Committee for the Review of Instructional Materials (CRIM) has reviewed many options and will be sending materials that remain under consideration to our campuses for review before Spring Break.

The feedback provided by parents and community members will be shared with the CRIM before resources are selected.

post_text:
Former AMCHS Information Technology teacher Bart Taylor is the recipient of the 2019 National ACTE Carl Perkins Community Service Award. This award recognizes individuals who have used Career and Technical Education (CTE) to make a significant impact on their community and demonstrated leadership in programs and activities that promote student involvement in community service.

Throughout Taylor’s 18-year tenure as a CTE teacher, he has coordinated and engaged in service projects that have accumulated over 1,500 service hours, and he has raised over $80,000 in grant funds to support his program and over $1,000,000 in funds for local education foundations.

#SuccessCSISD

Sorry for the inconvenience.

Want to receive emergency notifications via text message?

Step 1: Make sure that CSISD has your wireless number in our student information database. If you gave CSISD your wireless number in the registration process we have it. If not, please call your school and provide them with that information.

Step 2: Simply text “yes” to the number 67587.

Step 3: You will know you were successful, if you receive a reply message from SchoolMessenger.

post_text:
Each year, campuses across CSISD participate in a food drive to benefit the Brazos Valley Food Bank, and each year our community relentlessly supports this effort. This year, food items and cash donations totaled the equivalent of 172,257 pounds of food, equating to 143,547 meals the food bank will be able to provide to our local community. For the third year in a row, Oakwood Intermediate won the challenge for donating the most per student.
#SuccessCSISD
text:
Each year, campuses across CSISD participate in a food drive to benefit the Brazos Valley Food Bank, and each year our community relentlessly supports this effort. This year, food items and cash donations totaled the equivalent of 172,257 pounds of food, equating to 143,547 meals the food bank will be able to provide to our local community. For the third year in a row, Oakwood Intermediate won the challenge for donating the most per student.
#SuccessCSISD

post_text: Fitting tribute to a special educator we all miss.
shared_text:
College Station ISD Education Foundation is at South KnollElementary.
November 21, 2017 at 12:20 PM · College Station, TX ·

Today was a special day for CSISD and the Education Foundation. Friends, family and co-workers of Dr. Amy Anderson as well as Foundation board members and donors gathered at the South Knoll Elementary library to dedicate the Amy Anderson Literacy Legacy fund. In a touching ceremony, Amy's husband, Sid Anderson and children, Allyse and Aiden were presented with challenge coins emblazoned with the project's logo. Coins were also presented to Amy's parents, Francine & Milam Schverak; program initiator, Mary Culpepper; major donor and friend, Gayle Wiggins of Lead4ward, and logo designer and friend, Jon Carpenter.

The Amy Anderson Literacy Legacy program provides a $10 book voucher to all Pre-K and Head Start children in CSISD to shop for books at their school's book fair and create their own home libraries while nurturing good and lasting reading habits. The Education Foundation is proud to support this initiative for many years to come! #EFProjectSMILE

College Station Theatre is proud to present this year's fall production, A Midsummer Night's Dream and Romeo & Juliet. Performances are November 9, 10, 11 and 13 at 7 p.m., with a matinee on November 11 at 1:00 p.m.
